WEBVTT

00:19.874 --> 00:29.746
Like the perjording a team, have the best day of the day.

00:54.978 --> 00:59.091
It's great to see you.

00:59.151 --> 01:00.756
Thanks for being here as always.

01:00.876 --> 01:08.018
It's wild to think like, man, we've only got two weeks left of regular porch gatherings here in 2025.

01:08.258 --> 01:09.840
Man, I'm glad you're here this week.

01:09.860 --> 01:10.781
We've got next week.

01:10.882 --> 01:15.227
I think God has really big things in store and then Christmas at the porch is going to be amazing too.

01:15.328 --> 01:19.233
So thanks for making time to be here with us in Dallas, Texas.

01:19.593 --> 01:26.242
We love what God's doing amongst young adults here in our city, but we also love what he's doing in the lives of young adults all over the nation.

01:26.342 --> 01:29.106
I know that you don't get to see it, but man, we get

01:29.282 --> 01:40.094
We get correspondence from different people, and particularly our poor slide locations where God is doing a similar work there that he's doing here, and that is an amazing thing to see.

01:40.194 --> 01:45.059
Special shout out to our poor slide locations, Midland, Wheaton, Boise, specifically.

01:45.380 --> 01:51.827
We love you guys, and we hope to track with what God's gonna do the next two weeks, as well as in the future.

01:52.948 --> 01:54.610
Well, I remember

01:55.298 --> 01:59.524
I was nine years old when I encountered insecurity for the very first time.

02:00.566 --> 02:02.488
At least that's the first time that I can remember it.

02:03.350 --> 02:12.783
I was running for fourth grade class representative and after making posters that said, vote for Kylan, you'll be smiling.

02:14.826 --> 02:18.692
I came up short of actually winning.

02:18.712 --> 02:20.434
I came up.

02:20.802 --> 02:25.406
in second place, fast forward from there to my senior year of high school.

02:25.546 --> 02:32.872
I remember I'd put my campaign woes behind me and I decided in this moment to run for student council president.

02:32.913 --> 02:34.514
And I was doing so against one of my best friends.

02:34.534 --> 02:36.636
So I thought to myself, hey, it'll be great.

02:36.956 --> 02:37.296
I'll win.

02:37.537 --> 02:37.837
I'll win.

02:38.017 --> 02:38.577
It doesn't matter.

02:38.657 --> 02:41.480
Either one of us will go, but I knew deep down I really wanted this thing.

02:41.500 --> 02:47.425
And so I felt well positioned to serve the people and to be voted in by those people.

02:47.445 --> 02:50.788
Because at that point, I was on the football team.

02:50.768 --> 02:56.316
The leader amongst my peers, I knew that I was genuinely well-liked amongst people around me.

02:56.436 --> 03:13.761
I was destined for Texas A&M, and despite it all, once the ballots were tallied, I found that I, again, came in second place, and I was not sufficient to serve my friends the way that I wanted.

03:13.781 --> 03:17.366
I looked at myself, and I had no posters to blame any longer.

03:17.406 --> 03:20.210
Now it just felt as if I wasn't good enough.

03:20.674 --> 03:21.577
fast forward from there.

03:21.697 --> 03:29.463
I did end up going to Texas A&M and as I was at Texas A&M, I got to serve for a campus ministry that I genuinely love.

03:29.503 --> 03:32.754
Like this was something so unexpected.

03:32.802 --> 03:38.587
And yet when I got there and I found myself enrolled as one of their volunteers, it was the best experience.

03:38.607 --> 03:43.972
Like I met Jesus for the first time and I genuinely, I fell in love with the scriptures.

03:44.032 --> 03:46.214
I was getting the chance to serve my peers.

03:46.294 --> 04:00.566
And as I was doing all this, an opportunity came, my senior year of college to step into a potential leadership role because a vacancy had finally come open and it was a dream of mine to step into that position, serve the students of our campus.

04:00.666 --> 04:02.788
And yet you didn't get to apply for

04:02.768 --> 04:03.750
these leadership positions.

04:03.790 --> 04:08.718
Instead, the staff would come along, they would tap you on the shoulder and they'd pull you in and appoint you to position.

04:08.758 --> 04:11.783
I was praying that they would do it with me, but they didn't.

04:12.824 --> 04:21.499
Instead, they selected somebody different from a different team altogether because they estimated that there were no suitable leaders on our team.

04:23.081 --> 04:23.602
I want to hurt.

04:25.026 --> 04:29.470
And then after I graduated, I found myself working my first full-time job.

04:29.590 --> 04:32.833
It was in a company that I really loved amongst the people that I really loved.

04:32.853 --> 04:35.475
They were young and they were innovative and ambitious.

04:35.515 --> 04:38.117
They were the kind of people that I wanted to be associated with.

04:38.157 --> 04:40.800
And I liked my job, but there was a new job coming open.

04:40.820 --> 04:47.586
I was like, man, I've got to hop into that thing because that is the kind of position where I could really see myself sitting and staying while I could drop roots.

04:47.626 --> 04:55.012
I could cement sort of a type of experience in this corporate environment that will last the test of time.

04:54.992 --> 05:03.682
I put my application in and I went through the entire interview process, one, two, three interviews, and naturally I came up second.

05:04.323 --> 05:18.920
Again, they went with someone different, someone unexpected, and yet, though I wanted to be there so badly, in that moment, for me, it felt like they didn't want me to be there nearly as badly in response.

05:20.682 --> 05:24.306
Insecurity is a really big part of my story.

05:25.090 --> 05:38.994
And I could go on, but I tell you that because I think some of these moments in my life are reflective of some of the moments in this room, like you have experienced your own insecurities because it is

05:39.074 --> 05:44.379
extremely prevalent in the lives of people, but particularly young adults.

05:44.399 --> 06:03.255
Like you think about yourself and you assess yourself in comparison to others and you find yourself insecure, insecure in the things that you have or have not achieved, insecure in the way that you do look, insecure in the eyes of your heroes and not measuring up to what they would want, insecure at the possibility of failure.

06:03.395 --> 06:09.060
And because you feel this way, what ends up happening is you change yourself, you look at yourself

06:09.040 --> 06:14.469
and deem yourself insufficient, and so you start to contort your identity to become more than you actually are.

06:14.509 --> 06:19.638
And so you go from being insecure to now becoming an imposter, which isn't just some of us, it's a lot of us.

06:19.978 --> 06:27.891
According to the American Psychological Association, 82% of adults report facing feelings of imposter syndrome.

06:28.773 --> 06:30.616
What's imposter syndrome?

06:30.636 --> 06:31.858
It's feeling like a fraud.

06:32.226 --> 06:39.933
Like a phony, like a total sham, like you're sitting in rooms you're not supposed to be in, doing things that you feel totally inadequate to be doing.

06:40.173 --> 06:44.817
You're acting like something that you're not just because you feel the real you isn't actually enough.

06:45.197 --> 06:48.020
And so what you do is you think, no, I need to be someone smarter.

06:48.080 --> 06:49.281
I need to be someone sharper.

06:49.301 --> 06:50.262
I need to be someone stronger.

06:50.282 --> 06:51.122
I need to be someone prettier.

06:51.142 --> 06:52.223
I need to be someone wittier.

06:52.263 --> 06:53.344
I need to be someone better.

06:53.364 --> 06:54.505
I need to be someone impressive.

06:54.685 --> 06:57.968
Or like you think to yourself, I'm not sufficient.

06:58.169 --> 07:02.212
And so let me add to myself, whatever it is I'm lacking so that way I can be.

07:02.192 --> 07:06.824
And the repercussions of it are really damaging.

07:08.629 --> 07:10.253
I remember I had a friend in high school.

07:11.275 --> 07:12.338
It was an awesome guy.

07:12.834 --> 07:17.402
But he would change the way he talked, depending upon the people that he was with.

07:17.442 --> 07:19.345
You've got friends like this, some of them are sitting in this room.

07:19.766 --> 07:22.591
Like whenever he was in the locker room with the boys, he cussed like a sailor.

07:22.992 --> 07:26.658
Whenever he was in classroom with our teachers, he had the best manners.

07:26.979 --> 07:30.345
Whenever he was talking to a girl, he was the smoothest guy around.

07:30.385 --> 07:34.572
Like he would adjust the way he spoke, depending upon the crowd that he was with.

07:34.592 --> 07:38.098
And so one day I just asked him, I was like, hey, why do you do that?

07:40.354 --> 07:42.798
And he said something that I thought was really profound.

07:43.799 --> 07:46.583
He was like, people don't want the real me.

07:47.965 --> 07:49.207
They want their version of me.

07:51.611 --> 07:59.081
And at just 18 years old from the mouths of babes, like he said something that it just resonated deeply and it felt so very sad.

08:00.504 --> 08:05.150
And as true as it was then, I think that that is still true for many of us today.

08:05.210 --> 08:07.634
Now, let me be really clear.

08:08.706 --> 08:21.321
When I talk to you about changing things about yourself, I'm not saying that every time you change something about yourself, you're trying to make up for some deficiency you feel that everything you adapt is because you're insecure at heart.

08:21.341 --> 08:22.022
That's not the truth.

08:22.623 --> 08:27.228
The reality is many of you are wearing camo, though you've never worn camo in your life.

08:27.248 --> 08:32.114
And the reason you're wearing camo right now is because it's fashionable, not because you're insecure.

08:32.514 --> 08:33.335
Which I think is really funny.

08:33.355 --> 08:39.624
If you think hunters, people that wear camouflage on a regular basis, they are some of the least fashion conscious people in the world.

08:39.665 --> 08:42.809
And yet they're the ones setting the trends for young adults like you and I here today.

08:42.829 --> 08:43.670
But that's beside the point.

08:43.690 --> 08:49.379
The reason I bring that up is because you're allowed to change things because you like what you see on the outside.

08:51.282 --> 08:56.129
But many of us change things because we don't like what we see on the inside.

08:57.671 --> 09:02.418
We don't like who we are and we don't think others will either.

09:03.810 --> 09:05.994
We contort our identities.

09:07.898 --> 09:18.719
Like we change who we are socially, professionally, romantically, even spiritually.

09:19.721 --> 09:23.227
In the mental toll of doing so, it can be really devastating.

09:24.269 --> 09:26.674
Like just doing some research on this.

09:27.618 --> 09:43.426
If you indulge your low self-esteem or your insecurities, what happens is it could lead you to experience burnout because you're overworking your job, like your performance-oriented and you want to measure up in the eyes of other people until you're going to burn yourself out of a desire just to prove yourself to others.

09:44.128 --> 09:45.049
Maybe that's not the case for you.

09:45.069 --> 09:52.082
Maybe it's your field with an intense self-loathing because you're not achieving your goals and so you've

09:52.898 --> 09:58.286
You've grown dissatisfied with who you are and you're in capacity to actually attain the things that you want in life.

09:58.366 --> 09:58.947
Maybe it's not that.

09:58.987 --> 10:03.113
Maybe it's you're indulging in eating disorder because you're unhappy with your body.

10:03.133 --> 10:06.557
You look at yourself in the mirror and you wish you could change some things.

10:07.639 --> 10:08.240
Perhaps it's not that.

10:08.280 --> 10:10.323
Maybe you're filled with social anxiety.

10:10.844 --> 10:18.635
You come into places like this and all you want is to fit in and yet you feel like no matter how hard you try, it's so difficult to do that.

10:18.655 --> 10:19.316
Maybe that's not it.

10:19.356 --> 10:20.978
Maybe for you, you're battling trauma.

10:21.698 --> 10:26.023
because you endured some sort of past abuse that you never invited into your life.

10:26.043 --> 10:29.787
Someone stepped in and took something from you that was not theirs to have in the first place.

10:29.967 --> 10:37.956
And now you're left picking up the pieces and moving forward as well as you can, and you're actually traumatized.

10:37.976 --> 10:41.860
Maybe it's something else entirely, but here's the thing, people suffer in the face of their insecurity.

10:43.301 --> 10:51.250
And so tonight, I wanna give us, it's not just you, it's us, it's me too, a new perspective

10:51.554 --> 10:52.455
on insecurity.

10:52.475 --> 10:56.380
And the way that I want to do it is I want us to look at Psalm chapter 139.

10:56.981 --> 10:58.363
So if you have a Bible, you can pull it out.

10:58.383 --> 10:59.304
You can turn with me there.

10:59.905 --> 11:01.467
This is a really famous psalm.

11:01.507 --> 11:03.170
It's a beautiful passage of Scripture.

11:03.250 --> 11:09.258
Honestly, part of me kind of dreaded teaching it because it feels so esteemed and I want to honor it as well as I can.

11:09.278 --> 11:12.402
But I think it's the perfect place for us to come tonight.

11:12.674 --> 11:14.036
Now, here's what you gotta know.

11:14.076 --> 11:22.165
The reason we're in the Psalms is because as we've been working through this series called 2020, we're trying to get God's perspective on our mental health.

11:22.205 --> 11:24.908
And the reason for that is God is an emotional being.

11:24.928 --> 11:25.869
Do you ever think about that?

11:26.269 --> 11:33.257
Like all throughout the scripture, you can look at the way He interacts with people and you can see, man, that is a God build with emotion.

11:34.018 --> 11:38.483
And because we've been made in His image, we likewise have emotion, but oftentimes we don't know what to do with it.

11:39.204 --> 11:41.266
For many of us, emotion freaks us out.

11:41.538 --> 11:46.003
And so we stuff it way down deep inside where we can never see it and no one can ever see it either.

11:46.764 --> 11:48.666
Others of us, we love our emotions.

11:49.126 --> 11:52.310
We wear them out on our sleeve like an accessory for the world to admire.

11:52.350 --> 12:03.402
Like I don't know what your position is when it comes to your emotions, but the truth of the matter is the Bible would advise against both of those alternatives that you shouldn't just suppress your emotions and you shouldn't obsess over them.

12:04.503 --> 12:06.485
Rather, you should just express them.

12:06.506 --> 12:10.610
Like you should just tell God what it is you're actually feeling.

12:11.042 --> 12:20.594
We're to feel our emotions deeply, express our emotions honestly, and then process our emotions truthfully.

12:20.674 --> 12:24.306
We come to God and we give Him what we feel.

12:24.610 --> 12:29.616
And he comes to us and he gives us what he says in the union of those things.

12:29.756 --> 12:35.363
His truth and our feelings leads to a wholly integrated type of belief.

12:35.543 --> 12:39.088
One where we can love the Lord our God with our heart and our soul and our mind and our strength.

12:39.608 --> 12:42.191
That's the beauty of learning how to do this well.

12:42.472 --> 12:54.226
And the Psalms teach us better than most other places because we see the authors, the psalmist, David, the sons of Cora, Asoph, a variety of people do this themselves.

12:54.562 --> 12:56.665
And so tonight we're gonna see David do it himself.

12:57.946 --> 13:04.815
But before we can actually see what the right perspective is on this problem, we need to understand the problem.

13:04.835 --> 13:06.137
That's what we've been doing in this series.

13:06.177 --> 13:14.748
We've been trying to really take each sort of mental health disorder or issue and unpack it a little bit at the beginning before we apply God's word to it specifically.

13:14.988 --> 13:16.150
And so that's what I wanna do with you here.

13:16.630 --> 13:22.738
You see what we find is that in Psalm 139, it helps us to understand the problem of insecurity.

13:23.234 --> 13:26.258
If you look at it, it's 24 total verses.

13:26.979 --> 13:32.366
And those 24 verses break into four different sections, each of six verses a piece.

13:33.167 --> 13:35.771
And those four sections tell us something really important.

13:35.811 --> 13:40.597
They help us to identify the source for much of our insecurity.

13:41.238 --> 13:42.540
And so I thought it would just be helpful.

13:42.620 --> 13:48.468
In an effort to understand the problem, let's just talk about these four sections before we study them together.

13:48.488 --> 13:49.309
Does that sound good to you?

13:49.790 --> 13:50.351
So here it is.

13:51.352 --> 13:52.914
What do these four sections say?

13:53.602 --> 13:57.349
And where might your insecurity be particularly rooted?

13:57.389 --> 14:04.001
The first one is there can be insecurity from what you've done, what you've done.

14:04.743 --> 14:09.832
So this specifically comes from shame you feel over actions you've taken.

14:09.872 --> 14:15.122
These are the things you did, the things you said, or the things you thought.

14:15.682 --> 14:27.999
It could be that you're ashamed of how you handled a past relationship, ashamed of how you treated an old friend, ashamed of how you took advantage of someone else for your own benefit, how you made fun of someone just to get a rise out of other people.

14:28.179 --> 14:37.172
I don't know what it is for you, but it's really important for us to consider what have we done that might be producing insecurity in our life.

14:37.192 --> 14:41.618
And so to help you figure that out, I've got a diagnostic question for you, a series of them.

14:41.922 --> 14:44.206
that will help us to process these four categories.

14:44.326 --> 14:50.616
The right diagnostic question for shame over what you've done would be, what is your biggest regret in life?

14:51.437 --> 14:52.719
What's your biggest regret in life?

14:53.100 --> 14:55.985
If an answer springs top of mind, then that tells you.

14:56.285 --> 14:59.350
Man, I've probably got some insecurities rooted in things that I've done in the past.

14:59.390 --> 15:00.011
See how that works?

15:00.051 --> 15:00.632
Okay, number two.

15:01.734 --> 15:04.178
The second would be insecurity from where you've been.

15:04.546 --> 15:07.149
So this one isn't about shame from actions you've taken.

15:07.249 --> 15:10.212
It's about shame from situations you've faced.

15:10.673 --> 15:13.216
So it could be that you're ashamed of where you grew up.

15:13.696 --> 15:15.278
You're ashamed of the family you come from.

15:15.318 --> 15:18.902
It could be that you're ashamed of the college you went to or that you didn't go to college.

15:18.922 --> 15:22.846
It could be that you're ashamed that you had a marriage that failed and now you're divorced.

15:22.866 --> 15:26.110
It could be you're ashamed of the job you sit in or the job you don't.

15:26.230 --> 15:29.874
It could be, it's shame rooted in a particular situation.

15:30.722 --> 15:32.944
So here's a good diagnostic question for you.

15:33.025 --> 15:38.931
If you're trying to discern, am I insecure about some place I've come from or some where I've been?

15:38.951 --> 15:44.737
The question is what part of my story am I most embarrassed about?

15:45.919 --> 15:48.061
What part of my story am I most embarrassed by?

15:49.022 --> 15:58.753
If something just screams straight to mind, then that's probably some insecurity sourced in a place you've been, somewhere you were.

15:58.773 --> 15:59.794
Third one.

16:00.930 --> 16:02.894
can be insecurity from how you're made.

16:03.436 --> 16:15.122
This one is all about shame, not from your actions, not from your situation, but from your distinctions, those little uniquenesses, the things that make you who you are.

16:15.458 --> 16:17.781
It could be that you're ashamed of how you look.

16:17.821 --> 16:19.183
You're ashamed of how your voice sounds.

16:19.223 --> 16:21.827
You don't like the way your personality is expressed.

16:21.847 --> 16:25.752
You wish you could change something that is intrinsically true about who you are.

16:25.792 --> 16:27.174
You're not where you want to be in life.

16:27.475 --> 16:28.957
You wish you weren't so emotional.

16:29.277 --> 16:32.782
This is the area that most people statistically are insecure.

16:33.943 --> 16:41.334
So a good question, if you're trying to identify if this is where your insecurity is sourced, is what would I change about myself if I could?

16:42.856 --> 16:44.498
What would I change about myself if I could?

16:44.962 --> 16:58.596
Again, if I pose that to you and something comes very quickly to the mind, there's a good chance that you have some insecurities wrapped up and who you are and how you're made.

16:59.737 --> 17:07.464
And then the fourth one is insecurity from why you're here or why you do what you do.

17:08.145 --> 17:11.328
This one is not about action, not about situation, not about distinction.

17:11.368 --> 17:13.170
This one's all about motivation.

17:13.986 --> 17:25.238
So it could be that even though you would never admit it, you're actually ashamed of the reason you have that job or you date that girl or you hang out with those friends or you buy nice things.

17:27.140 --> 17:29.903
And that's because your motivation isn't as innocent as you'd like.

17:30.443 --> 17:40.754
It could be that your motivation for having that job is just because it makes you feel powerful, not because it's actually doing good or serving people.

17:41.186 --> 17:47.014
It could be that you're dating that girl, you're dating that guy just because it feels good to be needed and you get approval from them.

17:47.615 --> 17:50.599
That's a very selfish reason to be in a relationship.

17:50.659 --> 17:56.327
It could be that you buy nice things because it just makes you feel important and it actually makes you feel better than other people.

17:57.429 --> 18:01.234
All of these are not good reasons to do what you do.

18:01.890 --> 18:06.257
And so a helpful question, just a diagnose, man, like, is this my personal insecurity?

18:06.577 --> 18:16.833
The root of so much of my low self-esteem would be what area of my life do I justify most?

18:18.956 --> 18:20.859
What area of your life do you justify most?

18:22.301 --> 18:27.269
If you have to justify it, you probably don't have a very good reason for doing it.

18:27.289 --> 18:28.210
See how that works?

18:29.218 --> 18:34.286
Again, these questions, they don't help us solve our insecurities, but they do help us understand them.

18:34.367 --> 18:35.528
And like, where do they come from?

18:35.809 --> 18:41.739
And as we actually understand our insecurities, what we realize is insecurity ain't cute.

18:43.281 --> 18:48.570
But it's easy just to talk about insecurities because everybody's got them, but insecurities are not cute.

18:48.590 --> 18:49.512
They're dangerous.

18:50.333 --> 18:53.298
Like really insecurity is an attack on self.

18:54.434 --> 19:00.683
And so a good word for insecurity, a synonymous description, is insecurity is basically the same as self-hate.

19:01.765 --> 19:04.810
That there's something in you you do not like.

19:05.130 --> 19:10.078
And so you are willing to do whatever it takes to change that part of yourself.

19:11.039 --> 19:16.507
Sure, maybe it's because you think you'll be better, but ultimately it's because you think you couldn't get worse.

19:18.851 --> 19:23.538
We have to understand what God has to say about self-hate.

19:24.482 --> 19:36.220
And so to help us figure it out, we're going to look at Psalm 139, because although your problem may be self-hate, your perspective can be self-forgetfulness.

19:37.682 --> 19:41.067
It can be self-forgetfulness, which I know probably catches you off the guard a little bit.

19:41.087 --> 19:41.808
You're like, wait, hold on.

19:41.848 --> 19:43.891
So the solution to self-hate is self-forgetfulness.

19:44.592 --> 19:46.014
Wouldn't it naturally be the opposite of hate?

19:46.054 --> 19:47.076
Wouldn't it be self-love?

19:47.456 --> 19:48.498
Like, shouldn't I just

19:48.866 --> 19:57.174
Book a couple of 60-minute massages, get some emotions with the girls at brunch, make sure that I'm taking naps in front of the TV as it washes over me on Sundays and football is playing.

19:57.915 --> 20:03.640
There, should I just book my next trip and explore whatever my next national park is?

20:03.660 --> 20:07.784
Like, shouldn't I do something that takes the pressure off that makes me feel good?

20:07.824 --> 20:10.246
No.

20:10.266 --> 20:18.354
I mean, there's nothing intrinsically wrong with that stuff, but that is not going to deliver you from self-hate.

20:18.978 --> 20:24.106
You see, the path out of self-hate isn't self-love, it's self-forgetfulness.

20:24.867 --> 20:30.396
It's realizing, I don't need to give myself more attention.

20:31.217 --> 20:33.741
I need to give God more attention.

20:34.222 --> 20:43.717
And as I set my eyes upon Him, He who is worthy, He who is better, He who is infinitely good, I actually begin to see myself a little bit differently.

20:45.400 --> 20:46.962
Because as I see God rightly,

20:47.298 --> 20:49.621
